{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35757"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"3464"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year old woman presents after vomiting a small quantity of fresh blood. When she woke up this morning she felt nauseated and then vomited. She has never had anything like this before. Her only other current health issues are hypertension and osteoarthritis, for which she takes perindopril and paracetamol. The physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn endoscopy is performed and this is a view of the proximal stomach (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cameron\u0027s ulcer","Adenocarcinoma","Gastric ulcer","Carcinoid","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows a well circumscribed tumour protruding into the lumen of the proximal stomach. The overlying mucosa is largely intact. The umbilicated appearance at the apex suggests an area of recent ulceration. This has all the characteristics of a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAreas of mucosal ulceration sometime occur where the diaphragm impinges on the stomach where in a hiatus hernia and this is known as a Cameron\u0027s ulcer (Image 1). Adenocarcinoma involves the mucosa and as such, there would be large areas of ulceration in a tumour of this size (Image 2). Most carcinomas of the stomach do not present with overt bleeding and these patients would usually have other symptoms, such as anorexia and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGastric ulcers are usually flush with the mucosal surface and have a pale base to the ulcer (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarcinoids can have this appearance, but they tend to be much smaller (Image 4) and are much less common than gastrointestinal stromal tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumours are an uncommon, but well recognised cause of gastrointestinal bleeding."],"references":["Akahoshi K, Oya M, Koga T, et al. Current clinical management of gastrointestinal stromal tumor. World J Gastroenterol 2018; 24: 2806-817. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30018476/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35757"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"542"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20489"},{"type":"media","id":"20490"},{"type":"media","id":"20491"},{"type":"media","id":"20492"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/542"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/002f0716-3c61-468e-b42d-b04afedeacf2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/002f0716-3c61-468e-b42d-b04afedeacf2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":597,"height":497}},{"type":"media","id":"20489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20489"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/G1B9ItlhfZThTcQHxK37Ca1tz5VPEy.jpg","